than a dozen
French towns for being overtly
religious.

03:38.785 --> 03:43.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The law had wide public support,
but activists
from one town took it to the
highest court

03:43.423 --> 03:44.491 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Paris today.

03:44.524 --> 03:47.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Judges ruled it should be
suspended.

03:47.894 --> 03:57.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: It's against the civil
freedom of religion,
and now the decision of the
Conseil d'Etat

03:57.871 --> 03:59.639 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is final.

03:59.673 --> 04:03.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN GEISSLER: As absurd as
this all may
seem, it's important to remember
the context.

04:03.677 --> 04:08.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
France has suffered a series of
terror attacks
over recent months, and the
country feels

04:08.448 --> 04:10.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
