And you have decided to vote for
Clinton.

19:42.915 --> 19:43.983 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARISSA BAPTISTA: Absolutely,
yes.

19:44.016 --> 19:45.251 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why?

19:45.284 --> 19:50.556 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARISSA BAPTISTA: It was
probably because
I didn't like Trump.

19:50.589 --> 19:56.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think if there were other
Republican candidates
that were maybe a little more
moderate, then

19:56.729 --> 19:59.765 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I could be swayed to vote the
other side.

19:59.799 --> 20:01.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: To vote against
Clinton.

20:01.100 --> 20:02.635 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

20:02.668 --> 20:04.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARISSA BAPTISTA: To vote
Republican, which
I have never done in the past.

20:04.537 --> 20:07.106 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What is it about
Clinton?

20:07.139 --> 20:08.974 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You sound hesitant?

20:09.008 --> 20:11.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARISSA BAPTISTA: It's not
necessarily that
I'm hesitant.

20:11.677 --> 20:13.579 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think I just don't know
enough.

20:13.612 --> 20:18.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we were talking about,
you know, how
much time have you spent just
listening to

20:18.617 --> 20:22.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of the rhetoric or just the
information
that is coming out on TV?

20:23.022 --> 20:23.989 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
I work.

20:24.023 --> 20:25.257 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I have three young children.

20:25.291 --> 20:27.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, a lot of my information
doesn't come from
the news.

20:27.760 --> 20:29.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It comes from what I see on the
Internet.

20:29.395 --> 20:32.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Tom, what about
you, as you
look at the choices?

20:32.531 --> 20:40.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM SMITH: I feel like the
economic mess that
we're a part of now goes way
back, and both

20:40.139 --> 20:43.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
parties bear equal
responsibility.

20:43.476 --> 20:49.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The losers have been the lower
half or the
lower -- at this point, maybe,
90 percent

20:49.048 --> 20:53.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Americans, but certainly the
lower half.

20:53.919 --> 20:58.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think either of the
choices right
now are going to serve that
lower half.

20:58.924 --> 21:00.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Clinton or Trump?

21:00.059 --> 21:02.495 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TOM SMITH: Clinton or Trump.

21:02.528 --> 21:09.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, for me, the power of
appointments is
really critical for the future
of the country,

21:09.435 --> 21:15.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Supreme Court, the attorney
general, EPA,
just down the line.

21:15.574 --> 21:21.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton, I have more confidence
in who her
appointees would be than I --
than if Trump

21:21.647 --> 21:22.615 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
were president.

21:22.648 --> 21:24.350 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Farah, what about
you?

21:24.383 --> 21:30.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FARAH IMAM: I do tend to agree
with Democratic
Party when it comes to social
policy.

21:30.456 --> 21:36.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I comes down to if I had to
choose between
Trump or Clinton, I'm
conflicted.

21:36.295 --> 21:40.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I had to choose between only
those two,
then maybe I wouldn't vote.

21:40.199 --> 21:41.467 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But knowing that I had...

21:41.500 --> 21:42.735 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

21:42.768 --> 21:43.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Could you imagine
yourself
voting for Clinton?

21:43.802 --> 21:45.437 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
FARAH IMAM: Yes.

21:45.471 --> 21:46.438 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

21:46.472 --> 21:47.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's just difficult.

21:47.473 --> 21:50.910 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why?

21:50.943 --> 21:57.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FARAH IMAM: There is a lack of
sincerity that
I feel with her.

21:57.483 --> 22:01.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I know some people that I
speak with are,
like, oh, you're just saying
that because

22:01.520 --> 22:02.488 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
she's a woman.

22:02.521 --> 22:05.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I'm a woman, too, so it's
not that.

22:05.724 --> 22:07.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's, I don't find her
relatable.

22:08.027 --> 22:18.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't feel like she can, even
though she's
a mother, she's a working
mother, she just

22:18.070 --> 22:23.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- she has a hard time relating
to a broader
population.

22:23.742 --> 22:27.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I want to come
back to you,
Bill.

22:27.680 --> 22:29.682 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You're a traditional Republican.

22:29.715 --> 22:31.550 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We wouldn't expect you to
support the Democrat.

22:31.584 --> 22:35.154 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But did you even give her any
thought in this
election?

22:35.187 --> 22:37.389 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BILL LUPINACCI: It's a
possibility.

22:37.423 --> 22:38.958 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I doubt I'm going to vote for
her.

22:38.991 --> 22:40.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I seriously doubt.

22:40.793 --> 22:47.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But vilifying her and making her
into -- as
the right has done, into this
caricature is

22:47.633 --> 22:48.934 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
just wrong.

22:48.968 --> 22:52.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm more likely to vote for
neither a Democrat
or a Republican.

22:52.137 --> 22:54.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm looking at both Gary Johnson
and Jill
Stein.

22:54.840 --> 22:59.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I'm struck that,
in a state
where Hillary Clinton is
supposedly polling,

22:59.378 --> 23:04.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know, 10 points ahead,
that there
is no one here who is
enthusiastic for Hillary

23:04.283 --> 23:05.251 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Clinton.

23:05.284 --> 23:07.052 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Am I hearing you correctly?

23:07.086 --> 23:09.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARISSA BAPTISTA: Actually, now
that I think
about it, I think, because of
her position

23:09.655 --> 23:14.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
within the Democratic Party, so
she falls
in lines with things that
typical Democrats

23:14.793 --> 23:21.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
support, pro-choice,
pro-immigration, stronger
restriction on like gun laws, or
tightening

23:21.200 --> 23:23.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
up those gun laws.

23:23.135 --> 23:29.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think she falls in line
with the Democratic
Party, the platform, so, in
that, I would

23:29.508 --> 23:31.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
say that I would vigorously
support her.

23:31.844 --> 23:33.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Would plan to
vote for her?

23:33.746 --> 23:35.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARISSA BAPTISTA: Oh,
absolutely, yes.

23:35.147 --> 23:39.218 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TOM SMITH: And I will vote for
her, for sure.

23:39.251 --> 23:42.988 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't imagine a country run by
Trump.

23:43.022 --> 23:47.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I want to try to
sum this all
up by asking you all whether you
think it's

23:47.459 --> 23:51.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
possible for the country to come
together,
or are we just destined, at
least for the

23:51.096 --> 23:53.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
next number of years, to be
divided?

23:53.532 --> 23:55.334 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Corey?

23:55.367 --> 24:00.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
COREY SOLVAN: I think,
unfortunately, I think
we're looking at four more years
of division.

24:00.205 --> 24:01.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You would like to...

24:01.373 --> 24:02.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: No matter who is
elected, you're
saying?

24:02.274 --> 24:03.242 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
COREY SOLVAN: Yes.

24:03.275 --> 24:05.044 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

24:05.077 --> 24:06.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You would like to hope and wish
for it to
be different, but we have come
so far apart,

24:06.879 --> 24:10.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's going to take time to start
healing and
coming back to a middle ground
on everyday

24:10.749 --> 24:12.351 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
issues that affect all of us.

24:12.384 --> 24:13.619 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Bill, what do you
think?

24:13.652 --> 24:15.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can the country come together
under these
circumstances?

24:15.654 --> 24:20.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL LUPINACCI: What I'm hoping
for, what
I think could be possibly the
best for the

24:21.026 --> 24:26.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
country, is if these
independents get enough
vote, because people are so
disgusted with

24:27.032 --> 24:31.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
both the Republicans and the
Democrats, that
these two independents, Gary
Johnson and Jill

24:31.403 --> 24:36.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Stein, get enough votes that it
puts the fear
of God into them and saying, oh,
maybe four

24:36.608 --> 24:38.977 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
years from now, a third party
can win.

24:39.011 --> 24:41.880 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's going to be almost
impossible for them
to win this year.

24:41.914 --> 24:45.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But maybe it will scare them
enough to say,
one of these parties just might
take it in

24:45.818 --> 24:48.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
four years because the country
is fed up.

24:48.754 --> 24:55.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Does anybody see
coming together,
or do we just live with this
division?

24:55.427 --> 25:01.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FARAH IMAM: This nation was
built on hope
and perseverance and renewed
chances.

25:01.467 --> 25:06.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I feel like, no matter what,
we will find
ways to come together again.

25:06.872 --> 25:10.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We will find topics to come
together again.

25:10.843 --> 25:15.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we're all kind of aching
for it, no
matter Republican, Democrat,
independent.

25:15.814 --> 25:23.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we all kind of need
that, that moment
of unity again, because we're
all kind of

25:23.288 --> 25:26.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
like, oh, my gosh, the ship is
sinking.

25:27.025 --> 25:29.461 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But -- so that's -- so, I do
have hope.

25:29.495 --> 25:32.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, we're
going to leave
it there.

25:32.231 --> 25:33.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We thank you all very much.

25:33.332 --> 25:35.434 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is a lot more we could
talk about tonight.

25:35.467 --> 25:43.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this has really been a
wonderful conversation
and I thank you all very much.

25:43.742 --> 25:54.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That brings us
to the analysis
of Shields and Brooks.

25:54.520 --> 25:57.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and
New York Times columnist David
Brooks.

25:57.990 --> 26:01.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's start with your reactions
to what you
saw, this group of voters.

26:01.827 --> 26:04.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: It's always great
to hear the
voices of real voters.

26:04.930 --> 26:10.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, they're -- you know, we
see polls,
and it's 57 percent, we figure
everybody's

26:10.135 --> 26:11.870 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
monolithic.

26:11.904 --> 26:15.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And yet you get -- what you get
is, you get
the texture in the conversation
like that.

26:15.541 --> 26:23.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I found Alison really almost
compelling,
the woman who had voted for
Barack Obama in

26:23.048 --> 26:30.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
2008 and really felt that she
and the demographic
of, I guess, white American
voters had been

26:30.889 --> 26:32.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
neglected and forgotten.

26:33.025 --> 26:38.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just -- in the past eight
years, and Democrats'
attention to other agendas.

26:38.430 --> 26:44.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I just -- I found the voices
just really
revealing.

26:44.570 --> 26:49.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And most of all, it shows the
lack of enthusiasm
about this election.

26:49.441 --> 26:55.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When 51 percent of Republicans,
according
to Gallup poll, and 42 percent
of Democrats

26:55.380 --> 27:00.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
say they wish their party had
nominated somebody
else, I think it was reflected
in Judy's session.

27:00.819 --> 27:02.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, first, I
disagree with
Mark.

27:02.688 --> 27:03.655 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think we are real voters.

27:03.689 --> 27:04.656 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

27:04.690 --> 27:06.458 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Do we not bleed?

27:06.492 --> 27:07.459 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

27:07.493 --> 27:09.995 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: But, yes, I'm
really shocked.

27:10.028 --> 27:14.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like a lot of people one runs
across, a lot
of people in that focus group
were -- just

27:14.299 --> 27:18.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
couldn't imagine a Trump
presidency, but found
Clinton distrustworthy.

27:18.570 --> 27:22.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then say she wins -- and
according to
the upshot out of my newspaper,
it's like

27:22.474 --> 27:24.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
an 88 percent chance or
something like that.

27:24.510 --> 27:28.614 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But say that we go to an
inaugural or we go
into an administration with
someone the country

27:28.647 --> 27:30.182 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
fundamentally doesn't trust.

27:30.215 --> 27:33.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what does that do to the
morale of the
country?

27:33.051 --> 27:36.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And is there a way she can
become more trustworthy,
where she can reintroduce
herself in some

27:36.989 --> 27:39.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way, maybe after an election,
not in the heat
of a campaign?

27:39.424 --> 27:44.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Somehow, it just seems so
dispiriting, if
she does win, that we would go
through four

27:44.429 --> 27:49.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years where people feel this
personal distrust
for the commander in chief.

27:49.234 --> 27:51.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That can't be good for the
country, if it
stays like that.

27:51.403 --> 27:56.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Today, there
was even a
tepid endorsement by Bush
adviser Paul Wolfowitz,

27:56.141 --> 28:00.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
saying that he would vote for
Clinton, but
really it just came down to this
choice between

28:00.546 --> 28:02.381 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the lesser of two evils.

28:02.414 --> 28:07.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It seems so much that these
campaigns right
now is positioning about not
that our candidate

28:07.319 --> 28:08.287 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is not so great.

28:08.320 --> 28:09.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's just that the other
candidate is worse.

28:09.621 --> 28:11.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

28:11.390 --> 28:14.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the last endorsement in the
world that
Hillary Clinton wants at this
point is the

28:14.493 --> 28:21.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
man who made the case publicly
to go to war
in Iraq and admitted that the
argument was

28:21.266 --> 28:26.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- consensus argument was on
weapons of mass
destruction, because that was
what everybody

28:26.438 --> 28:28.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
could get behind.

28:28.307 --> 28:36.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the cause -- cause for going
to war was
just, you know, a contrivance.

28:36.415 --> 28:43.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's not -- Hillary Clinton
probably doesn't
want to be reminded of her
support for that

28:43.221 --> 28:44.790 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
venture.

28:44.823 --> 28:49.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think she probably now has
enough Republican
foreign policy endorsements.

28:49.561 --> 28:51.363 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

28:51.396 --> 28:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Also this
week, we talked
a little bit about the rise of
the alt-right

28:55.434 --> 28:57.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
movement, the white supremacist
movement.

28:57.669 --> 29:01.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have got this week one
candidate calling
the other a racist, and then him
responding

