43:54.365 --> 44:05.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Lionfish have
voracious
appetites that are upsetting
coral reef ecosystems

44:05.142 --> 44:07.178 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from Rhode Island to Venezuela.

44:07.211 --> 44:11.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a new nonprofit company has
an unusual
plan to restore balance to those
environments

44:11.749 --> 44:13.518 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
before it's too late.

44:13.551 --> 44:17.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the latest edition of our
online series
"ScienceScope," science producer
Nsikan Akpan

44:17.154 --> 44:18.155 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has the scoop.

44:18.189 --> 44:21.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NSIKAN AKPAN: The lionfish is an
invasive
species.

44:21.425 --> 44:23.828 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's also Darwin's nightmare.

44:23.861 --> 44:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In its native home of the
Indo-Pacific, the
lionfish is a fierce,
unrelenting predator.

44:28.599 --> 44:34.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the mid-1980s, exotic pets,
including lionfish,
became popular in the U.S.
Scientists suspect

44:34.372 --> 44:37.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pet owners eventually dumped
their adult lionfish
in the Atlantic.

44:37.608 --> 44:41.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The lionfish now threatens
ecosystems up and
down the Atlantic.

44:41.646 --> 44:42.613 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But they should watch out.

44:42.647 --> 44:45.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A new robot is entering the
fray.

44:45.182 --> 44:51.889 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Meet the lionfish terminator.

44:51.923 --> 45:06.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To learn about this robot, we
traveled here
to Bermuda, where we teamed up
with the Nekton

45:06.037 --> 45:07.838 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mission.

45:07.872 --> 45:12.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This 30 scientific organizations
and companies
wants to conduct one of the
largest marine

45:12.476 --> 45:14.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
life surveys in history.

45:14.145 --> 45:17.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OLIVER STEEDS, Mission Director,
Nekton: These
divers are the first 1,900
meters.

45:17.381 --> 45:19.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then these extraordinary
submersibles
go down even further.

45:19.650 --> 45:24.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have adapted some with some
of the latest
filming and scientific
equipment, so, we can

45:24.288 --> 45:28.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sample, we can study, and we can
research,
as welcome as taking scientists
down into

45:28.092 --> 45:29.560 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those depths.

45:29.594 --> 45:32.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NSIKAN AKPAN: Of the earth's
oceans, only
5 percent have been explored.

45:32.563 --> 45:36.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That means we know more about
the moon than
the water that covers 70 percent
of the Earth.

45:36.934 --> 45:42.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Nekton wants to fill the
knowledge gap by
making a baseline measurement of
ocean health.

45:42.473 --> 45:48.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's because our are facing
threats, including
the spread of invasive species
like the lionfish.

45:48.746 --> 45:53.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chris Flook is a collector of
marine specimens
for the Bermuda Aquarium Museum
and Zoo.

45:53.417 --> 45:57.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he was one of the first to
notice the
region's lionfish invasion 16
years ago.

45:57.088 --> 46:00.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS FLOOK, Bermuda Aquarium
Museum and Zoo:
But then very quickly, I started
to notes

46:00.524 --> 46:04.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, over time, we were losing
small fish
from these areas where I
traditionally went

46:04.395 --> 46:05.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and found lots of small juvenile
fish.

46:06.030 --> 46:09.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And lionfish were becoming more
and more common.

46:09.166 --> 46:13.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, by about 2007, we actually
started a culling
program in Bermuda to tackle
these invasive

46:13.738 --> 46:15.506 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
species.

46:15.539 --> 46:18.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NSIKAN AKPAN: Now known as the
Bermuda Lionfish
Task Force, the team holds daily
dives and

46:18.542 --> 46:21.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fishing tournaments to rid their
waters of
these invaders.

46:21.545 --> 46:26.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Its members consist of
recreational swimmers,
professional divers and even
local scientists

46:26.083 --> 46:27.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like Dr. Gretchen
Goodbody-Gringley.

46:27.451 --> 46:29.286 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

46:29.320 --> 46:30.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GRETCHEN GOODBODY-GRINGLEY,
Bermuda Institute
of Ocean Sciences: The lionfish
are a threat

46:30.855 --> 46:33.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the ecosystem because, first
and foremost,
they're voracious predators.

46:33.057 --> 46:39.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they consume an exorbitant
amount of food,
more than any other potential
predator out

46:39.764 --> 46:42.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
there right now.

46:42.867 --> 46:49.674 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
All of the white part is
solidified fat, because
it's unique to lionfish that
they overconsume,

46:49.707 --> 46:53.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
