liver disease.

46:53.277 --> 46:57.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NSIKAN AKPAN: This is because
smaller fish
in this region don't recognize
the lionfish

46:57.648 --> 46:58.616 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as a threat.

46:58.649 --> 47:01.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They swim right up to it and get
gobbled up.

47:01.152 --> 47:03.954 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Basically, the lionfish just
opens its mouth.

47:03.988 --> 47:09.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a big dilemma, because the
task force
can tackle lionfish only in
shallow water.

47:09.593 --> 47:14.999 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
But in Bermuda,
Goodbody-Gringley has found
most lionfish live 200 feet
below the surface.

47:15.032 --> 47:18.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
That depth is largely
inaccessible to the
average sport diver.

47:18.369 --> 47:21.439 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that's not too deep for a
robot.

47:21.472 --> 47:25.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Goodbody-Gringley and Nekton
have teamed with
a new nonprofit called RISE, or
Robots in

47:25.543 --> 47:29.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Service of the Environment,
that is developing
a lionfish-hunting robot.

47:29.213 --> 47:31.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEOFFREY GARDNER, Robots in the
Service of
the Environment: The leading
candidate is

47:31.082 --> 47:36.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
based on an electrofishing
techniques, where
if you put the lionfish between
two electrodes

47:36.454 --> 47:41.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and apply an electric current,
